# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: clojure
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:clojure/about-rationale] Customers and stakeholders have substantial investments in, and are comfortable with the performance, security and stability of, industry-standard platforms like the JVM.
[src:clojure/about-rationale] While Java developers may envy the succinctness, flexibility and productivity of dynamic languages, they have concerns about running on customer-approved infrastructure, access to their existing code base and libraries, and performance.
[src:clojure/about-rationale] In addition, they face ongoing problems dealing with concurrency using native threads and locking.
[src:clojure/about-rationale] Clojure is an effort in pragmatic dynamic language design in this context.
[src:clojure/about-rationale] It endeavors to be a general-purpose language suitable in those areas where Java is suitable.
[src:clojure/about-rationale] It reflects the reality that, for the concurrent programming future, pervasive, unmoderated mutation simply has to go.
[src:clojure/about-rationale] The result is robust, practical, and fast.
[src:clojure/about-rationale] Clojure has a distinctive approach to state and identity.
[src:clojure/about-rationale] Why did I write yet another programming language?
[src:clojure/about-rationale] Here’s an outline of some of the motivating ideas behind Clojure.
[src:clojure/about-rationale] In short, I think Clojure occupies a unique niche as a functional Lisp for the JVM with strong concurrency support.
[src:clojure/about-rationale] Check out some of the features or get started with Clojure.
[src:clojure/clojure] Like most other Lisps, Clojure's syntax is built on S-expressions that are first parsed into data structures by a Lisp reader before being compiled.
[src:clojure/clojure] Clojure's reader supports literal syntax for maps, sets, and vectors along with lists, and these are compiled to the mentioned structures directly.
[src:clojure/clojure] Clojure treats code as data and has a Lisp macro system.
[src:clojure/clojure] Clojure is a Lisp-1 and is not intended to be code-compatible with other dialects of Lisp, since it uses its own set of data structures incompatible with other Lisps.
[src:clojure/clojure] Clojure advocates immutability and immutable data structures and encourages programmers to be explicit about managing identity and its states.
[src:clojure/clojure] This focus on programming with immutable values and explicit progression-of-time constructs is intended to facilitate developing more robust, especially concurrent, programs that are simple and fast.
[src:clojure/clojure] While its type system is entirely dynamic, recent efforts have also sought the implementation of a dependent type system.
[src:clojure/clojure] The language was created by Rich Hickey in the mid-2000s, originally for the Java platform; the language has since been ported to other platforms, such as the Common Language Runtime (.NET).
[src:clojure/clojure] Hickey continues to lead development of the language as its benevolent dictator for life.
[src:clojure/clojure] Rich Hickey is the creator of the Clojure language.
[src:clojure/clojure] Hickey started working on Clojure in 2005 and spent about two and a half years working on Clojure before releasing it publicly in October 2007, much of that time working exclusively on Clojure with no outside funding.
[src:clojure/clojure] Stephanie Hickey, his wife, helped to design the language by a being an active listener and participating in discussions without writing any code.
[src:clojure/clojure] At the end of this time, Hickey sent an email announcing the language to some friends in the Common Lisp community.
[src:clojure/clojure] Clojure's name, according to Hickey, is a word play on the programming concept "closure" incorporating the letters C, L, and J for C#, Lisp, and Java respectively—three languages which had a major influence on Clojure's design.
[src:clojure/clojure] Rich Hickey developed Clojure because he wanted a modern Lisp for functional programming, symbiotic with the established Java platform, and designed for concurrency.
[src:clojure/clojure] He has also stressed the importance of simplicity in programming language design and software architecture, advocating for loose coupling, polymorphism via protocols and type classes instead of inheritance, stateless functions that are namespaced instead of methods or replacing syntax with data.
[src:clojure/clojure] Clojure's approach to state is characterized by the concept of identities, which are represented as a series of immutable states over time.
[src:clojure/clojure] Since states are immutable values, any number of workers can operate on them in parallel, and concurrency becomes a question of managing changes from one state to another.
[src:clojure/clojure] For this purpose, Clojure provides several mutable reference types, each having well-defined semantics for the transition between states.
[src:clojure/clojure] Clojure runs on the Java platform and as a result, integrates with Java and fully supports calling Java code from Clojure, and Clojure code can be called from Java, too.
[src:clojure/clojure] The community uses tools such as Clojure command-line interface (CLI) or Leiningen for project automation, providing support for Maven integration.
[src:clojure/clojure] These tools handle project package management and dependencies and are configured using Clojure syntax.
[src:clojure/clojure] As a Lisp dialect, Clojure supports functions as first-class objects, a read–eval–print loop (REPL), and a macro system.
[src:clojure/clojure] Clojure's Lisp macro system is very similar to that of Common Lisp with the exception that Clojure's version of the backquote (termed "syntax quote") qualifies symbols with their namespace.
[src:clojure/clojure] This helps prevent unintended name capture, as binding to namespace-qualified names is forbidden.
[src:clojure/clojure] It is possible to force a capturing macro expansion, but it must be done explicitly.
[src:clojure/clojure] Clojure does not allow user-defined reader macros, but the reader supports a more constrained form of syntactic extension.
[src:clojure/clojure] Clojure supports multimethods and for interface-like abstractions has a protocol based polymorphism and data type system using records, providing high-performance and dynamic polymorphism designed to avoid the expression problem.
[src:clojure/clojure] Clojure has support for lazy sequences and encourages the principle of immutability and persistent data structures.
[src:clojure/clojure] As a functional language, emphasis is placed on recursion and higher-order functions instead of side-effect-based looping.
[src:clojure/clojure] Automatic tail call optimization is not supported as the JVM does not support it natively; it is possible to do so explicitly by using the `recur` keyword.
[src:clojure/clojure] For parallel and concurrent programming Clojure provides software transactional memory, a reactive agent system, and channel-based concurrent programming.
[src:clojure/clojure] Clojure 1.7 introduced reader conditionals by allowing the embedding of Clojure, ClojureScript and ClojureCLR code in the same namespace.
[src:clojure/clojure] Transducers were added as a method for composing transformations.
[src:clojure/clojure] Transducers enable higher-order functions such as map and fold to generalize over any source of input data.
[src:clojure/clojure] While traditionally these functions operate on sequences, transducers allow them to work on channels and let the user define their own models for transduction.
[src:clojure/clojure] In addition to those elements, it supports extensibility through the use of *tags*, which consist of the character `#` followed by a symbol.
[src:clojure/clojure] When encountering a tag, the reader passes the value of the next element to the corresponding handler, which returns a data value.
[src:clojure/clojure] For example, this could be a tagged element: `#myapp/Person {:first "Fred" :last "Mertz"}`, whose interpretation will depend on the appropriate handler of the reader.
[src:clojure/clojure] This definition of extension elements in terms of the others avoids relying on either convention or context to convey elements not included in the base set.
[src:clojure/clojure] The primary platform of Clojure is Java, but other target implementations exist.
[src:clojure/clojure] The most notable of these is ClojureScript, which compiles to ECMAScript 3 (or newer ES5 or ES5-strict, up to ES-2021, and ES-next possible) and ClojureCLR, a full port on the .NET platform, interoperable with its ecosystem.
[src:clojure/clojure] Tooling for Clojure development has seen significant improvement over the years.
[src:clojure/clojure] In addition to the tools provided by the community, the official Clojure command-line interface (CLI) tools have also become available on Linux, macOS, and Windows since Clojure 1.9.
[src:clojure/clojure] The development process is restricted to the Clojure core team, though issues are publicly visible at the Clojure JIRA project page.
[src:clojure/clojure] Anyone can ask questions or submit issues and ideas at ask.clojure.org.
[src:clojure/clojure] If it's determined that a new issue warrants a JIRA ticket, a core team member will triage it and add it.
[src:clojure/clojure] JIRA issues are processed by a team of screeners and finally approved by Rich Hickey.
[src:clojure/clojure] With continued interest in functional programming, Clojure's adoption by software developers using the Java platform has continued to increase.
[src:clojure/clojure] The language has also been recommended by software developers such as Brian Goetz, Eric Evans, James Gosling, Paul Graham, and Robert C.
[src:clojure/clojure] ThoughtWorks, while assessing functional programming languages for their Technology Radar, described Clojure as "a simple, elegant implementation of Lisp on the JVM" in 2010 and promoted its status to "ADOPT" in 2012.
[src:clojure/clojure] In the "JVM Ecosystem Report 2018" (which was claimed to be "the largest survey ever of Java developers"), that was prepared in collaboration by Snyk and Java Magazine, ranked Clojure as the 2nd most used programming language on the JVM for "main applications".
[src:clojure/clojure] Clojure is used in industry by firms such as Apple, Atlassian, Funding Circle, Netflix, Nubank, Puppet, and Walmart as well as government agencies such as NASA.
[src:clojure/clojure] It has also been used for creative computing, including visual art, music, games, and poetry.
[src:clojure/clojure] In the 2023 edition of Stack Overflow Developer Survey, Clojure was the fourth most *admired* in the category of programming and scripting languages, with 68.51% of the respondents who have worked with it last year saying they would like to continue using it.
[src:clojure/clojure] In the *desired* category, however it was marked as such by only 2.2% of the surveyed, whereas the highest scoring JavaScript was *desired* by 40.15% of the developers participating in the survey.
[src:clojure/data-structures] Clojure has a rich set of data structures.
[src:clojure/data-structures] nil is a possible value of any data type in Clojure. nil has the same value as Java null.
[src:clojure/data-structures] The Clojure conditional system is based around nil and false, with nil and false representing the values of logical falsity in conditional tests - anything else is logical truth.
[src:clojure/data-structures] In addition, nil is used as the end-of-sequence sentinel value in the sequence protocol.
[src:clojure/data-structures] Clojure provides full support for JVM primitive values by default, allowing high performance, idiomatic Clojure code for numeric applications.
[src:clojure/data-structures] Clojure also supports the Java boxed number types derived from java.lang.Number, including BigInteger and BigDecimal, plus its own Ratio type.
[src:clojure/data-structures] By default Clojure operates with natural numbers as instances of Java’s long primitive type.
[src:clojure/data-structures] When a primitive integer operation results in a value that is too large to be contained in a primitive value, a java.lang.ArithmeticException is thrown.
[src:clojure/data-structures] Clojure provides a set of alternative math operators suffixed with an apostrophe: +', -', *', inc', and dec'.
[src:clojure/data-structures] These operators auto-promote to BigInt upon overflow, but are less efficient than the regular math operators.
[src:clojure/data-structures] Division of integers that can’t be reduced to an integer yields a ratio, i.e.
[src:clojure/data-structures] 22/7 = 22/7, rather than a floating point or truncated value.
[src:clojure/data-structures] BigInts and floating point types are "contagious" across operations.
[src:clojure/data-structures] That is, any integer operation involving a BigInt will result in a BigInt, and any operation involving a double or float will result in a double.
[src:clojure/data-structures] Numeric literals for BigInt and BigDecimal are specified using a postfix N and M respectively.
[src:clojure/data-structures] Computation: + - * / inc dec quot rem min max Auto-promoting computation: +' -' *' inc' dec' Comparison: == < <= > >= zero? pos? neg?
[src:clojure/data-structures] Keywords are symbolic identifiers that evaluate to themselves.
[src:clojure/data-structures] Like Symbols, they have names and optional namespaces, both of which are strings.
[src:clojure/data-structures] The leading ':' is not part of the namespace or name.
[src:clojure/data-structures] Keywords implement IFn for invoke() of one argument (a map) with an optional second argument (a default value).
[src:clojure/data-structures] For example `(:mykey my-hash-map :none)` means the same as `(get my-hash-map :mykey :none)`.
[src:clojure/data-structures] Symbols are identifiers that are normally used to refer to something else.
[src:clojure/data-structures] They can be used in program forms to refer to function parameters, let bindings, class names, class members, and global vars.
[src:clojure/data-structures] They have names and optional namespaces, both of which are strings.
[src:clojure/data-structures] Symbols can have metadata (see with-meta).
[src:clojure/data-structures] Symbols, just like Keywords, implement IFn for invoke() of one argument (a map) with an optional second argument (a default value).
[src:clojure/data-structures] For example `('mysym my-hash-map :none)` means the same as `(get my-hash-map 'mysym :none)`.
[src:clojure/data-structures] All of the Clojure collections are immutable and persistent.
[src:clojure/data-structures] In particular, the Clojure collections support efficient creation of 'modified' versions, by utilizing structural sharing, and make all of their performance bound guarantees for persistent use.
[src:clojure/data-structures] The collections are efficient and inherently thread-safe.
[src:clojure/data-structures] Collections are represented by abstractions, and there may be one or more concrete realizations.
[src:clojure/data-structures] In particular, since 'modification' operations yield new collections, the new collection might not have the same concrete type as the source collection, but will have the same logical (interface) type.
[src:clojure/data-structures] All the collections support count for getting the size of the collection, conj for 'adding' to the collection, and seq to get a sequence that can walk the entire collection, though their specific behavior is slightly different for different types of collections.
[src:clojure/data-structures] Because collections support the seq function, all of the sequence functions can be used with any collection.
[src:clojure/data-structures] The Java collection interfaces specify algorithms for Lists, Sets, and Maps in calculating hashCode() values.
[src:clojure/data-structures] All Clojure collections conform to these specifications in their hashCode() implementations.
[src:clojure/data-structures] Clojure provides its own hash computations that provide better hash properties for collections (and other types), known as the *hasheq* value.
[src:clojure/data-structures] The `IHashEq` interface marks collections that provide the `hasheq()` function to obtain the hasheq value.
[src:clojure/data-structures] In Clojure, the hash function can be used to compute the hasheq value.
[src:clojure/data-structures] Ordered collections (vector, list, seq, etc) must use the following algorithm for calculating hasheq (where hash computes hasheq).
[src:clojure/data-structures] Note that unchecked-add-int and unchecked-multiply-int are used to get integer overflow calculations.
[src:clojure/data-structures] Unordered collections (maps, sets) must use the following algorithm for calculating hasheq.
[src:clojure/data-structures] A map entry is treated as an ordered collection of key and value.
[src:clojure/data-structures] Note that unchecked-add-int is used to get integer overflow calculations.
[src:clojure/data-structures] The mix-collection-hash algorithm is an implementation detail subject to change.
[src:clojure/data-structures] They implement the ISeq interface directly.
[src:clojure/data-structures] (Note that the empty list implements ISeq as well, however the `seq` function will always return `nil` for an empty sequence.) count is O(1). conj puts the item at the front of the list.
[src:clojure/data-structures] Create a list: list list* Treat a list like a stack: peek pop Examine a list: list?
[src:clojure/data-structures] A Vector is a collection of values indexed by contiguous integers.
[src:clojure/data-structures] Vectors support access to items by index in log32N hops. count is O(1). conj puts the item at the end of the vector.
[src:clojure/data-structures] Vectors also support rseq, which returns the items in reverse order.
[src:clojure/data-structures] Vectors implement IFn, for invoke() of one argument, which they presume is an index and look up in themselves as if by nth, i.e. vectors are functions of their indices.
[src:clojure/data-structures] Vectors are compared first by length, then each element is compared in order.
[src:clojure/data-structures] Create a vector: vector vec vector-of Examine a vector: get nth peek rseq vector?
[src:clojure/data-structures] A Map is a collection that maps keys to values.
[src:clojure/data-structures] Two different map types are provided - hashed and sorted.
[src:clojure/data-structures] Hash maps require keys that correctly support hashCode and equals.
[src:clojure/data-structures] Sorted maps require keys that implement Comparable, or an instance of Comparator.
[src:clojure/data-structures] Sorted map also supports rseq, which returns the entries in reverse order.
[src:clojure/data-structures] Maps implement IFn, for invoke() of one argument (a key) with an optional second argument (a default value), i.e. maps are functions of their keys. nil keys and values are ok.
[src:clojure/data-structures] Create a new map: hash-map sorted-map sorted-map-by 'change' a map: assoc dissoc select-keys merge merge-with zipmap Examine a map: get contains? find keys vals map?
[src:clojure/data-structures] Often many map instances have the same base set of keys, for instance when maps are used as structs or objects would be in other languages.
[src:clojure/data-structures] StructMaps support this use case by efficiently sharing the key information, while also providing optional enhanced-performance accessors to those keys.
[src:clojure/data-structures] StructMaps are in all ways maps, supporting the same set of functions, are interoperable with all other maps, and are persistently extensible (i.e. struct maps are not limited to their base keys).
[src:clojure/data-structures] The only restriction is that you cannot dissociate a struct map from one of its base keys.
[src:clojure/data-structures] A struct map will retain its base keys in order.
[src:clojure/data-structures] StructMaps are created by first creating a structure basis object using create-struct or defstruct, then creating instances with struct-map or struct.
[src:clojure/data-structures] When doing code form manipulation it is often desirable to have a map which maintains key order.
[src:clojure/data-structures] An array map is such a map - it is simply implemented as an array of key val key val… As such, it has linear lookup performance, and is only suitable for *very small* maps.
[src:clojure/data-structures] New ArrayMaps can be created with the array-map function.
[src:clojure/data-structures] Note that an array map will only maintain sort order when un-'modified'.
[src:clojure/data-structures] Subsequent assoc-ing will eventually cause it to 'become' a hash-map.
[src:clojure/data-structures] Clojure provides basic set operations like union / difference / intersection, as well as some pseudo-relational algebra support for 'relations', which are simply sets of maps - select / index / rename / join.
[src:clojure/learn-functions] Functions are first-class and can be passed-to or returned-from other functions.
[src:clojure/learn-functions] Most Clojure code consists primarily of pure functions (no side effects), so invoking with the same inputs yields the same output.
[src:clojure/learn-functions] This function has a single parameter `name`, however you may include any number of parameters in the params vector.
[src:clojure/learn-functions] Functions can be defined to take different numbers of parameters (different "arity").
[src:clojure/learn-functions] Different arities must all be defined in the same `defn` - using `defn` more than once will replace the previous function.
[src:clojure/learn-functions] Each arity is a list `([param*] body*)`.
[src:clojure/learn-functions] The body can contain any number of expressions and the return value is the result of the last expression.
[src:clojure/learn-functions] This function declares two arities (0 parameters and 1 parameter).
[src:clojure/learn-functions] The 0-parameter arity calls the 1-parameter arity with a default value to print.
[src:clojure/learn-functions] Functions may also define a variable number of parameters - this is known as a "variadic" function.
[src:clojure/learn-functions] The variable parameters must occur at the end of the parameter list.
[src:clojure/learn-functions] They will be collected in a sequence for use by the function.
[src:clojure/learn-functions] The beginning of the variable parameters is marked with `&`.
[src:clojure/learn-functions] This function takes a parameter `greeting` and a variable number of parameters (0 or more) that will be collected in a list named `who`.
[src:clojure/learn-functions] You can see that when `println` prints `who`, it is printed as a list of two elements that were collected.
[src:clojure/learn-functions] Because the anonymous function has no name, it cannot be referred to later.
[src:clojure/learn-functions] Rather, the anonymous function is typically created at the point it is passed to another function.
[src:clojure/learn-functions] Here we defined the anonymous function in the function position of a larger expression that immediately invokes the expression with the argument.
[src:clojure/learn-functions] Many languages have both statements, which imperatively do something and do not return a value, and expressions which do.
[src:clojure/learn-functions] Clojure has **only** expressions that return a value.
[src:clojure/learn-functions] We’ll see later that this includes even flow control expressions like `if`.
[src:clojure/learn-functions] It might be useful to think of `defn` as a contraction of `def` and `fn`.
[src:clojure/learn-functions] The `fn` defines the function and the `def` binds it to a name.
[src:clojure/learn-functions] There is a shorter form for the `fn` anonymous function syntax implemented in the Clojure reader: `#()`.
[src:clojure/learn-functions] This syntax omits the parameter list and names parameters based on their position.
[src:clojure/learn-functions] Nested anonymous functions would create an ambiguity as the parameters are not named, so nesting is not allowed.
[src:clojure/learn-functions] One common need is an anonymous function that takes an element and wraps it in a vector.
[src:clojure/learn-functions] This form will wrap in a vector **and** try to invoke the vector with no arguments (the extra pair of parentheses).
[src:clojure/learn-functions] The `apply` function invokes a function with 0 or more fixed arguments, and draws the rest of the needed arguments from a final sequence.
[src:clojure/learn-functions] The final argument **must** be a sequence.
[src:clojure/learn-functions] All 4 of these calls are equivalent to `(f 1 2 3 4)`.
[src:clojure/learn-functions] `apply` is useful when arguments are handed to you as a sequence but you must invoke the function with the values in the sequence.
[src:clojure/learn-functions] `let` binds symbols to values in a "lexical scope".
[src:clojure/learn-functions] A lexical scope creates a new context for names, nested inside the surrounding context.
[src:clojure/learn-functions] Names defined in a `let` take precedence over the names in the outer context.
[src:clojure/learn-functions] Each `let` can define 0 or more bindings and can have 0 or more expressions in the body.
[src:clojure/learn-functions] This `let` expression creates two local bindings for `x` and `y`.
[src:clojure/learn-functions] The expression `(+ x y)` is in the lexical scope of the `let` and resolves x to 1 and y to 2.
[src:clojure/learn-functions] Outside the `let` expression, x and y will have no continued meaning, unless they were already bound to a value.
[src:clojure/learn-functions] The messenger function takes a `msg` argument.
[src:clojure/learn-functions] Here the `defn` is also creating lexical scope for `msg` - it only has meaning within the `messenger` function.
[src:clojure/learn-functions] Within that function scope, the `let` creates a new scope to define `a`, `b`, and `c`.
[src:clojure/learn-functions] If we tried to use `a` after the let expression, the compiler would report an error.
[src:clojure/learn-functions] The `fn` special form creates a "closure".
[src:clojure/learn-functions] It "closes over" the surrounding lexical scope (like `msg`, `a`, `b`, or `c` above) and captures their values beyond the lexical scope.
[src:clojure/learn-functions] 1) Define a function `greet` that takes no arguments and prints "Hello".
[src:clojure/learn-functions] 2) Redefine `greet` using `def`, first with the `fn` special form and then with the `#()` reader macro.
[src:clojure/learn-functions] 4) Define a function `do-nothing` which takes a single argument `x` and returns it, unchanged.
[src:clojure/learn-functions] In Clojure, this is the `identity` function.
[src:clojure/learn-functions] By itself, identity is not very useful, but it is sometimes necessary when working with higher-order functions.
[src:clojure/learn-functions] 5) Define a function `always-thing` which takes any number of arguments, ignores all of them, and returns the number `100`.
[src:clojure/learn-functions] 6) Define a function `make-thingy` which takes a single argument `x`.
[src:clojure/learn-functions] It should return another function, which takes any number of arguments and always returns x.
[src:clojure/learn-functions] In Clojure, this is the `constantly` function.
[src:clojure/learn-functions] 7) Define a function `triplicate` which takes another function and calls it three times, without any arguments.
[src:clojure/learn-functions] 8) Define a function `opposite` which takes a single argument `f`.
[src:clojure/learn-functions] It should return another function which takes any number of arguments, applies `f` on them, and then calls `not` on the result.
[src:clojure/learn-functions] The `not` function in Clojure does logical negation.
[src:clojure/learn-functions] In Clojure, this is the complement function.
[src:clojure/learn-functions] 9) Define a function `triplicate2` which takes another function and any number of arguments, then calls that function three times on those arguments.
[src:clojure/learn-functions] Re-use the function you defined in the earlier triplicate exercise.
[src:clojure/learn-functions] 11) Define a function that takes an HTTP URL as a string, fetches that URL from the web, and returns the content as a string.
[src:clojure/learn-functions] Hint: Using the java.net.URL class and its `openStream` method.
[src:clojure/learn-functions] Then use the Clojure `slurp` function to get the content as a string.
[src:clojure/learn-functions] In fact, the Clojure `slurp` function interprets its argument as a URL first before trying it as a file name.
[src:clojure/learn-functions] and returns another function which calls `f` on `x` plus any additional arguments.
[src:clojure/learn-functions] In Clojure, the `partial` function is a more general version of this.
[src:clojure/learn-functions] 13) Define a function `two-fns` which takes two functions as arguments, `f` and `g`.
[src:clojure/learn-functions] It returns another function which takes one argument, calls `g` on it, then calls `f` on the result, and returns that.
[src:clojure/learn-functions] That is, your function returns the composition of `f` and `g`.
[src:clojure/learn-syntax] Below are some examples of literal representations of common primitives in Clojure.
[src:clojure/learn-syntax] All of these literals are valid Clojure expressions.
[src:clojure/learn-syntax] The `;` creates a comment to the end of the line.
[src:clojure/learn-syntax] Sometimes multiple semicolons are used to indicate header comment sections, but this is just a convention.
[src:clojure/learn-syntax] Integers are read as fixed precision 64-bit integers when they are in range and arbitrary precision otherwise.
[src:clojure/learn-syntax] A trailing `N` can be used to force arbitrary precision.
[src:clojure/learn-syntax] Clojure also supports the Java syntax for octal (prefix `0`), hexadecimal (prefix `0x`) and arbitrary radix (prefix base, then `r`, e.g.
[src:clojure/learn-syntax] Ratios are provided as their own type combining a numerator and denominator.
[src:clojure/learn-syntax] Floating point values are read as double-precision 64-bit floats, or arbitrary precision with an `M` suffix.
[src:clojure/learn-syntax] The special symbolic values `##Inf`, `##-Inf`, and `##NaN` represent positive infinity, negative infinity, and "not a number" values respectively.
[src:clojure/learn-syntax] Strings are contained in double quotes and may span multiple lines.
[src:clojure/learn-syntax] Individual characters are represented with a leading backslash.
[src:clojure/learn-syntax] There are a few special named characters: `\newline` `\space` `\tab`, etc.
[src:clojure/learn-syntax] Unicode characters can be represented with `\uNNNN` or in octal with `\oNNN`.
[src:clojure/learn-syntax] Literal regular expressions are strings with a leading `#`.
[src:clojure/learn-syntax] These are compiled to java.util.regex.Pattern objects.
[src:clojure/learn-syntax] Symbols are composed of letters, numbers, and other punctuation and are used to refer to something else, like a function, value, namespace, etc.
[src:clojure/learn-syntax] Symbols may optionally have a namespace, separated with a forward slash from the name.
[src:clojure/learn-syntax] There are three special symbols that are read as different types - `nil` is the null value, and `true` and `false` are the boolean values.
[src:clojure/learn-syntax] Keywords start with a leading colon and always evaluate to themselves.
[src:clojure/learn-syntax] They are frequently used as enumerated values or attribute names in Clojure.
[src:clojure/learn-syntax] We’ll talk about these in much greater detail later - for now it’s enough to know that these four data structures can be used to create composite data.
[src:clojure/learn-syntax] Next we will consider how Clojure reads and evaluates expressions.
[src:clojure/learn-syntax] In Java, source code (.java files) are read as characters by the compiler (javac), which produces bytecode (.class files) which can be loaded by the JVM.
[src:clojure/learn-syntax] In Clojure, source code is read as characters by the Reader.
[src:clojure/learn-syntax] The Reader may read the source either from .clj files or be given a series of expressions interactively.
[src:clojure/learn-syntax] The Clojure compiler then produces the bytecode for the JVM.
[src:clojure/learn-syntax] Separating the Reader and the Compiler is a key separation that makes room for macros.
[src:clojure/learn-syntax] Macros are special functions that take code (as data), and emit code (as data).
[src:clojure/learn-syntax] Can you see where a loop for macro expansion could be inserted in the evaluation model?
[src:clojure/learn-syntax] This diagram illustrates the difference between syntax in green (the Clojure data structure produced by the Reader) and semantics in blue (how that data is understood by the Clojure runtime).
[src:clojure/learn-syntax] Most literal Clojure forms evaluate to themselves, **except** symbols and lists.
[src:clojure/learn-syntax] Symbols are used to refer to something else and when evaluated, return what they refer to.
[src:clojure/learn-syntax] Lists (as in the diagram) are evaluated as invocation.
[src:clojure/learn-syntax] In the diagram, (+ 3 4) is read as a list containing the symbol (+) and two numbers (3 and 4).
[src:clojure/learn-syntax] The first element (where + is found) can be called "function position", that is, a place to find the thing to invoke.
[src:clojure/learn-syntax] While functions are an obvious thing to invoke, there are also a few special operators known to the runtime, macros, and a handful of other invokable things.
[src:clojure/learn-syntax] Many languages have both statements and expressions, where statements have some stateful effect but do not return a value.
[src:clojure/learn-syntax] In Clojure, everything is an expression that evaluates to a value.
[src:clojure/learn-syntax] Some expressions (but not most) also have side effects.
[src:clojure/learn-syntax] Now let’s consider how we can interactively evaluate expressions in Clojure.
[src:clojure/learn-syntax] Sometimes it’s useful to suspend evaluation, in particular for symbols and lists.
[src:clojure/learn-syntax] For now, don’t worry too much about quote but you will see it occasionally in these materials to avoid evaluation of symbols or lists.
[src:clojure/learn-syntax] Most of the time when you are using Clojure, you will do so in an editor or a REPL (Read-Eval-Print-Loop).
[src:clojure/learn-syntax] Evaluate the data returned from #1 to yield a result (also Clojure data).
[src:clojure/learn-syntax] Print the result by converting it from data back to characters.
[src:clojure/learn-syntax] One important aspect of #2 is that Clojure always compiles the expression before executing it; Clojure is **always** compiled to JVM bytecode.
[src:clojure/learn-syntax] The box above demonstrates evaluating an expression (+ 3 4) and receiving a result.
[src:clojure/learn-syntax] Most REPL environments support a few tricks to help with interactive use.
[src:clojure/learn-syntax] In addition, there is a namespace `clojure.repl` that is included in the standard Clojure library that provides a number of helpful functions.
[src:clojure/learn-syntax] For now, you can treat that as a magic incantation.
[src:clojure/learn-syntax] We’ll unpack it when we get to namespaces.
[src:clojure/learn-syntax] We now have access to some additional functions that are useful at the REPL: `doc`, `find-doc`, `apropos`, `source`, and `dir`.
[src:clojure/learn-syntax] The `doc` function displays the documentation for any function.
[src:clojure/learn-syntax] The `doc` function prints the documentation for `+`, including the valid signatures.
[src:clojure/learn-syntax] The doc function prints the documentation, then returns nil as the result - you will see both in the evaluation output.
[src:clojure/learn-syntax] You can use the `apropos` command to find functions that match a particular string or regular expression.
[src:clojure/learn-syntax] If you’d like to see a full listing of the functions in a particular namespace, you can use the `dir` function.
[src:clojure/learn-syntax] As you go through this workshop, please feel free to examine the docstring and source for the functions you are using.
[src:clojure/learn-syntax] Exploring the implementation of the Clojure library itself is an excellent way to learn more about the language and how it is used.
[src:clojure/learn-syntax] It is also an excellent idea to keep a copy of the Clojure Cheatsheet open while you are learning Clojure.
[src:clojure/learn-syntax] The cheatsheet categorizes the functions available in the standard library and is an invaluable reference.
[src:clojure/learn-syntax] Now let’s consider some Clojure basics to get you going….
[src:clojure/learn-syntax] When you are evaluating things at a REPL, it can be useful to save a piece of data for later.
[src:clojure/learn-syntax] `def` is a special form that associates a symbol (x) in the current namespace with a value (7).
[src:clojure/learn-syntax] In most actual Clojure code, vars should refer to either a constant value or a function, but it’s common to define and re-define them for convenience when working at the REPL.
[src:clojure/learn-syntax] Note the return value above is `#'user/x` - that’s the literal representation for a var: `#'` followed by the namespaced symbol.
[src:clojure/learn-syntax] One of the most common things you do when learning a language is to print out values.
[src:clojure/learn-syntax] The human-readable forms will translate special print characters (like newlines and tabs) to their printed form and omit quotes in strings.
[src:clojure/learn-syntax] We often use `println` to debug functions or print a value at the REPL.
[src:clojure/learn-syntax] The println function has side-effects (printing) and returns nil as a result.
[src:clojure/learn-syntax] Note that "What is this:" above did not print the surrounding quotes and is not a string that the Reader could read again as data.
[src:clojure/learn-syntax] Now the printed result is a valid form that the Reader could read again.
[src:clojure/learn-syntax] Depending on context, you may prefer either the human form or the data form.
[src:clojure/learn-syntax] Rewrite the following algebraic expression as a Clojure expression: `( 7 + 3 * 4 + 5 ) / 10`.
