[src:clojure/reference-reader] Clojure is a homoiconic language, which is a fancy term describing the fact that Clojure programs are represented by Clojure data structures.
[src:clojure/reference-reader] This is a very important difference between Clojure (and Common Lisp) and most other programming languages - Clojure is defined in terms of the evaluation of data structures and **not** in terms of the syntax of character streams/files.
[src:clojure/reference-reader] It is quite common, and easy, for Clojure programs to manipulate, transform and produce other Clojure programs.
[src:clojure/reference-reader] That said, most Clojure programs begin life as text files, and it is the task of the *reader* to parse the text and produce the data structure the compiler will see.
[src:clojure/reference-reader] This is not merely a phase of the compiler.
[src:clojure/reference-reader] The reader, and the Clojure data representations, have utility on their own in many of the same contexts one might use XML or JSON etc.
[src:clojure/reference-reader] One might say the reader has syntax defined in terms of characters, and the Clojure language has syntax defined in terms of symbols, lists, vectors, maps etc.
[src:clojure/reference-reader] The reader is represented by the function read, which reads the next form (not character) from a stream, and returns the object represented by that form.
[src:clojure/reference-reader] Since we have to start somewhere, this reference starts where evaluation starts, with the reader forms.
[src:clojure/reference-reader] This will inevitably entail talking about data structures whose descriptive details, and interpretation by the compiler, will follow.
[src:clojure/reference-reader] Map literals can optionally specify a default namespace context for keys in the map using a `#:ns` prefix, where *ns* is the name of a namespace and the prefix precedes the opening brace `{` of the map.
[src:clojure/reference-reader] Additionally, `#::` can be used to auto-resolve namespaces with the same semantics as auto-resolved keywords.
[src:clojure/reference-reader] The behavior of the reader is driven by a combination of built-in constructs and an extension system called the read table.
[src:clojure/reference-reader] Entries in the read table provide mappings from certain characters, called macro characters, to specific reading behavior, called reader macros.
[src:clojure/reference-reader] Unless indicated otherwise, macro characters cannot be used in user symbols.
[src:clojure/reference-reader] As per above, yields a character literal.
[src:clojure/reference-reader] Example character literals are: `\a \b \c`.
[src:clojure/reference-reader] The following special character literals can be used for common characters: `\newline`, `\space`, `\tab`, `\formfeed`, `\backspace`, and `\return`.
[src:clojure/reference-reader] Unicode support follows Java conventions with support corresponding to the underlying Java version.
[src:clojure/reference-reader] A Unicode literal is of the form `\uNNNN`, for example `\u03A9` is the literal for Ω.
[src:clojure/reference-reader] Single-line comment, causes the reader to ignore everything from the semicolon to the end-of-line.
[src:clojure/reference-reader] Metadata is a map associated with some kinds of objects: Symbols, Lists, Vector, Sets, Maps, tagged literals returning an IMeta, and record, type, and constructor calls.
[src:clojure/reference-reader] The metadata reader macro first reads the metadata and attaches it to the next form read (see with-meta to attach meta to an object): `^{:a 1 :b 2} [1 2 3]` yields the vector `[1 2 3]` with a metadata map of `{:a 1 :b 2}`.
[src:clojure/reference-reader] A shorthand version allows the metadata to be a simple symbol or string, in which case it is treated as a single entry map with a key of `:tag` and a value of the (resolved) symbol or string, e.g.: `^String x` is the same as `^{:tag java.lang.String} x`.
[src:clojure/reference-reader] See `:param-tags` on how param-tags are used.
[src:clojure/reference-reader] Metadata can be chained in which case they are merged from right to left.
[src:clojure/reference-reader] For all forms other than Symbols, Lists, Vectors, Sets and Maps, `x is the same as 'x.
[src:clojure/reference-reader] For Symbols, syntax-quote *resolves* the symbol in the current context, yielding a fully-qualified symbol (i.e. namespace/name or fully.qualified.Classname).
[src:clojure/reference-reader] If a symbol is non-namespace-qualified and ends with '#', it is resolved to a generated symbol with the same name to which '_' and a unique id have been appended. e.g. x# will resolve to x_123.
[src:clojure/reference-reader] All references to that symbol within a syntax-quoted expression resolve to the same generated symbol.
[src:clojure/reference-reader] For Lists/Vectors/Sets/Maps, syntax-quote establishes a template of the corresponding data structure.
[src:clojure/reference-reader] The read table is currently not accessible to user programs.
[src:clojure/reference-reader] Clojure’s reader supports a superset of extensible data notation (edn).
[src:clojure/reference-reader] The edn specification is under active development, and complements this document by defining a subset of Clojure data syntax in a language-neutral way.
[src:clojure/reference-reader] Tagged literals are Clojure’s implementation of edn tagged elements.
[src:clojure/reference-reader] When Clojure starts, it searches for files named `data_readers.clj` or `data_readers.cljc` at the root of the classpath.
[src:clojure/reference-reader] The key in each pair is a tag that will be recognized by the Clojure reader.
[src:clojure/reference-reader] The value in the pair is the fully-qualified name of a Var which will be invoked by the reader to parse the form following the tag.
[src:clojure/reference-reader] by invoking the Var `#'my.project.foo/bar` on the vector `[1 2 3]`.
[src:clojure/reference-reader] The data reader function is invoked on the form AFTER it has been read as a normal Clojure data structure by the reader.
[src:clojure/reference-reader] For your own data reader functions, you should report errors by throwing instances of RuntimeException with messages providing error information.
[src:clojure/reference-reader] Reader tags without namespace qualifiers are reserved for Clojure.
[src:clojure/reference-reader] Default reader tags are defined in default-data-readers but may be overridden in `data_readers.clj` / `data_readers.cljc` or by rebinding *data-readers*.
[src:clojure/reference-reader] If no data reader is found for a tag, the function bound in *default-data-reader-fn* will be invoked with the tag and value to produce a value.
[src:clojure/reference-reader] If *default-data-reader-fn* is nil (the default), a RuntimeException will be thrown.
[src:clojure/reference-reader] If a `data_readers.cljc` is provided, it is read with the same semantics as any other cljc source file with reader conditionals.
[src:clojure/reference-reader] Clojure 1.4 introduced the *instant* and *UUID* tagged literals.
[src:clojure/reference-reader] Instants have the format `#inst "yyyy-mm-ddThh:mm:ss.fff+hh:mm"`.
[src:clojure/reference-reader] NOTE: Some of the elements of this format are optional.
[src:clojure/reference-reader] The default reader will parse the supplied string into a `java.util.Date` by default.
[src:clojure/reference-reader] Since *data-readers* is a dynamic var that can be bound, you can replace the default reader with a different one.
[src:clojure/reference-reader] If no data reader is found when reading a tagged literal, the *default-data-reader-fn* is invoked.
[src:clojure/reference-reader] You can set your own default data reader function and the provided tagged-literal function can be used to build an object that can store an unhandled literal.
[src:clojure/reference-reader] Clojure 1.7 introduced a new extension (.cljc) for portable files that can be loaded by multiple Clojure platforms.
[src:clojure/reference-reader] The primary mechanism for managing platform-specific code is to isolate that code into a minimal set of namespaces, and then provide platform-specific versions (.clj/.class or .cljs) of those namespaces.
[src:clojure/reference-reader] In cases where is not feasible to isolate the varying parts of the code, or where the code is mostly portable with only small platform-specific parts, 1.7 also introduced *reader conditionals*, which are supported only in cljc files and at the default REPL.
[src:clojure/reference-reader] Reader conditionals should be used sparingly and only when necessary.
[src:clojure/reference-reader] Reader conditionals are a new reader dispatch form starting with `#?` or `#?@`.
[src:clojure/reference-reader] Both consist of a series of alternating features and expressions, similar to `cond`.
[src:clojure/reference-reader] Every Clojure platform has a well-known "platform feature" - `:clj`, `:cljs`, `:cljr`.
[src:clojure/reference-reader] Each condition in a reader conditional is checked in order until a feature matching the platform feature is found.
[src:clojure/reference-reader] The reader conditional will read and return that feature’s expression.
[src:clojure/reference-reader] The expression on each non-selected branch will be read but skipped.
[src:clojure/reference-reader] A well-known `:default` feature will always match and can be used to provide a default.
[src:clojure/reference-reader] If no branches match, no form will be read (as if no reader conditional expression was present).
[src:clojure/reference-reader] The syntax for `#?@` is exactly the same but the expression is expected to return a collection that can be spliced into the surrounding context, similar to unquote-splicing in syntax quote.
[src:clojure/reference-reader] Use of reader conditional splicing at the top level is not supported and will throw an exception.
[src:clojure/reference-reader] The read and read-string functions optionally take a map of options as a first argument.
[src:clojure/reference-reader] However, note that the Clojure reader will *always* inject the platform feature :clj as well.
[src:clojure/reference-reader] For platform-agnostic reading, see tools.reader.
[src:clojure/reference-reader] If the reader is invoked with `{:read-cond :preserve}`, the reader conditional and non-executed branches will be preserved, as data, in the returned form.
[src:clojure/reference-reader] The reader-conditional will be returned as a type that supports keyword retrieval for keys with `:form` and a `:splicing?` flag.
[src:clojure/reference-reader] Read but skipped tagged literals will be returned as a type that supports keyword retrieval for keys with `:form` and `:tag` keys.
